tumour types","Detection of monoclonal antigen receptor gene rearrangements in lymphoid neoplasms","Detection of metastatic disease using radiological imaging"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003Edetection of monoclonal antigen receptor gene rearrangements in lymphoid neoplasms\u003C/strong\u003E. T-cell and B-cell tumours arise from single cells with unique antigen receptor gene rearrangements, while reactive (non-neoplastic) lymphoid proliferations contain many different lymphocyte clones with diverse antigen receptor gene rearrangements. Polymerase chain reaction (PCR) analysis of T-cell receptor or immunoglobulin genes can therefore distinguish between monoclonal (neoplastic) and polyclonal (reactive) lymphoid proliferations, aiding in diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReplacement of histopathological examination for all tumour types\u003C/strong\u003E - Molecular methods are not the primary modality for cancer diagnosis but rather complement traditional histopathology. They are particularly valuable in selected cases where morphology alone is insufficient.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIdentification of germline mutations in all cancer patients\u003C/strong\u003E - While germline mutation testing is important for detecting hereditary cancer predisposition in some patients, it is not routinely performed for all cancer patients and is primarily used for specific high-risk individuals or families.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeasurement of tumour marker proteins in peripheral blood\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes serological testing for tumour markers, which is different from molecular diagnostic techniques that analyze DNA or RNA.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDetection of metastatic disease using radiological imaging\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes radiological techniques rather than molecular diagnostic methods.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther important applications of molecular techniques in cancer include detecting specific chromosomal translocations in haematological malignancies and sarcomas, identifying genetic alterations that predict prognosis, monitoring minimal residual disease, guiding therapy with targeted drugs, and detecting mechanisms of drug resistance through liquid biopsies.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Molecular diagnostic techniques can distinguish between monoclonal (neoplastic) and polyclonal (reactive) lymphoid proliferations by analyzing antigen receptor gene rearrangements.","Specific chromosomal translocations detected by cytogenetic analysis or FISH can aid in the diagnosis of haematological malignancies and sarcomas.","Molecular testing can identify genetic alterations that predict prognosis and guide targeted therapy selection in cancer patients."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 7; pages 333."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79113"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20858"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79113","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79113"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-01T17:21:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-01T17:22:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13733"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96471"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroup